Case Study: UPI / Online Payment Fraud
UPI (Unified Payments Interface) fraud is one of the most common cybercrimes in India, where attackers trick users into transferring money through digital payment apps. This type of fraud mainly relies on social engineering rather than technical hacking.

A typical UPI fraud begins when the victim receives a call, SMS, or message on platforms like WhatsApp. The fraudster pretends to be a bank official, customer care executive, or even a buyer/seller from an online marketplace. First, they build trust by offering help, discounts, or warning about an urgent issue with the victim’s account. Next, they send a “collect request” or a fake payment link and ask the victim to approve it, claiming it will result in receiving money. In some cases, they ask for sensitive details like OTPs or UPI PINs.

The common targets are students, elderly people, and individuals who are new to digital payments. These users may not fully understand how UPI requests work, making them more vulnerable.

The consequences can be serious, including immediate financial loss, stress, and difficulty in recovering the money. In many cases, victims are unable to get refunds. This highlights the importance of awareness, verifying requests, and never sharing confidential details like OTPs or UPI PINs.
